aveley (Lancashire), or Staveley (Yorkshire). The placenames all derive from Old English <i>stæf</i> ‘staff, stave, rod’ (genitive plural <i>stafa</i>) + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare   Staveley  ."]},{"name":"Stabley","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Staveley   and   Stabler  , two names of different origins but whose pronunciations were much confused from the 17th century onward."]},{"name":"Stavely","meanings":["English: variant of   Staveley  ."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":35,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda Staveley was born in 1420, in Lancashire, England. She had at least 1 daughter with Ralph Staveley."},"et":{"1420–Deceased":"1420–Surnud","1417–1456":"1417–1456","1441–1493":"1441–1493","1420–Female":"1420–Surnud","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1441":"1441","1493":"1493","1417":"1417","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1420–Deceased":"1420–Kuollut","1417–1456":"1417–1456","1441–1493":"1441–1493","1420–Female":"1420–Kuollut","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1441":"1441","1493":"1493","1417":"1417","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"1420–Deceased":"1420–Décédée","1417–1456":"1417–1456","1441–1493":"1441–1493","1420–Female":"1420–Décédée","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1441":"1441","1493":"1493","1417":"1417","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Matilda Staveley est née en 1420, à Lancashire, Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Ralph Staveley."},"de":{"1420–Deceased":"1420–Verstorben","1417–1456":"1417–1456","1441–1493":"1441–1493","1420–Female":"1420–Verstorben","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1441":"1441","1493":"1493","1417":"1417","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","lifeSummary":"Matilda Staveley wurde 1420 in Lancashire, England geboren. Sie hatte mit Ralph Staveley mindestens 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"1420–Deceased":"1420–Desede","1417–1456":"1417–1456","1441–1493":"1441–1493","1420–Female":"1420–Desede","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1420":"1